The AMT Backup was first known as the OMC Backup. This early variant was produced in .380 ACP caliber in El Monte, California. OMC produced a short run of these pistols before the molds were purchased by Arcadia Machine & Tool, who took over production.

title: For Sale:  S&W 686-1
postcontent:
1988 Smith & Wesson Model 686-1, (The .357 Distinguished Combat Magnum - Stainless) chambered in .357 Magnum

This revolver is not accompanied by the original Box or Paperwork. 

About the Model 686 >
Smith & Wesson introduced the 686 "L" Frame Revolver in 1980. It is simply a Stainless Steel Version of the very popular Model 586 which was either Blued or Nickel Plated. The model 686 had the Goncalo Alves Hardwood grips standard until 1994 when S&W Switched to having Hogue supply them. Ascetically, I think the Wood looks much better.

This particular 668-1 has the "M" Stamp for the recall work being done by the factory. The recall was for the Firing Pin Bushing as it was found to weaken when using a steady diet of .357 Magnum Loads. It has the 6" barrel with Full Under-Lug. I am not the original owner so I cannot speak of round count but I personally put 24 flawless rounds through it myself. The changes for this revision (-1) are the "Radius Stud Package" and the "Floating Hand". The Single Action trigger on this beautiful S&W Wheel Gun is Amazing.

Features;
* "L" Frame with Square Butt
* Double / Single Action
* 6" Barrel Length
* 1/8" Serrated Ramped Front Sight with Red Insert
* Adjustable Micrometer Target Rear Sight
* Target Style Wood Stocks with Speed Loader Cutout
* 6 Shot Fluted Cylinder, .357 Mag, and .38 Special, and .38 Special +P
* Stainless Steel Finish

For location Reference, I am located About 35 miles South West of Savannah.

title: For Sale:  H&K VP 9 Factory New
postcontent:
In development for more than four years, the VP9 is Heckler & Koch’s latest handgun and the first striker fired HK since the renowned P7 series pistols were introduced in the 1980s.

Experience gained by HK engineers with the recent P30 pistol had a direct influence on the design of the VP9, but the VP9 breaks new ground with its integration of a unique striker firing system with an enhanced HK “light pull” trigger. The net result is trigger quality unequaled in any production striker fired handgun.

HK pioneered the first striker fired handguns, producing both the VP70 and P7 series, designs that impacted several models by HK competitors. But a superior trigger has eluded most striker fired pistol designs. The VP9 trigger surpasses those found on competitors. It has a short, light take-up with a solid, single action type break followed by a short positive reset.

The VP9 trigger has a consistent pre-travel pull with a positive wall/crisp break. Typically, striker fired guns have a pre-travel pull that increases in weight as you go through the trigger stroke. With the VP9, you have a less than noticeable pre-travel pull until the trigger reaches the engagement point of the fire control parts prior to trigger break.

The VP9 uses HK’s ergonomic handgun grip design that includes three changeable backstraps and six side panels— accommodating all hand sizes. Molded finger grooves in the front of the pistol’s grip also instinctively position an operator’s hand for optimal shooting. Only HK handguns have such a customized grip.

Although influenced by other HK models, the VP9 has all the hallmarks of the latest, state-of-the-art handgun. All controls are completely ambidextrous. Slide releases are present on both sides of the frame and the magazine release can be easily activated by left- or right-handed shooters.

Blue Book of guns has MSRP at $720 for the Rifle and $575 for 100% condition and Amazon is selling the scope new at $325.

This rifle is in immaculate condition.  The barrel went through a very slow and strict break in process right out of the box.  Mostly a hunting rifle.  Very low round count. Estimated round count under 200.

I have only fired about 50 rounds through this gun and it has cycled everything from cheap #8 trap loads to 00 buckshot to slugs without a hiccup and without needing to adjust any gas settings.  The VEPR 12 is the gold standard of the AK shotguns with a thicker RPK style 1.5mm receiver and a self-adjusting gas system, AR style loading, chrome lined barrel,  chamber,  receiver shaft and  gas chamber and last round bolt hold open.

This truly is a great shotgun!  I have over $2000 invested in this gun!
